node.text:
After executive chef David Shim (@chefdavidshim) and culinary director SK Kim (@chefskkim) ready 30 enormous buckets of kimchi to ferment for 10-14 days at Simon Kim’s (@simonkimnyc) Michelin-starred Cote in NYC (@cote_nyc), they step into their neon red dry-aging room to break down a slab of well-marbled rib-eye steak, dry-aged for 45 days. It’s just one piece out of the 3,000 pounds of beef they butcher per week for the Korean steakhouse, which combines the best parts of American steakhouse traditions with the grilling styles of Korean barbecue. 

Director/Producer/Editor: @DanielGeneen // Camera: @connorreidgram, @mur_f

node.title: How Master Chefs Run the World's Only Michelin-Starred Korean Steakhouse

node.text:
For the smoked pork rib tips at My Father’s Barbeque (@myfathersbbq), pitmaster Shalamar Lane (@chefshalamarlane) uses a traditional paprika and cumin spice rub, used by her Alabama-native father, that includes cracked black pepper and coarse salt often found in her mother’s Texas-style barbecue dishes. With a marriage of styles and techniques from both regions, but being served in California, chef Lane carries on her family traditions while also forging something entirely new.

Producer/Director: @Connorreidgram // Camera: @Connorreidgram, @Mur_F // Editor: @mike.imhoff

node.title: How Pitmaster Shalamar Lane Uses Family Traditions at My Father’s Barbeque

node.text:
Torre Lupara’s buffalo mozzarella is about an Italian as a product as you can get. The cheese is classified as DOP Mozzarella di Bufala, meaning everything from the feed the buffalo eat, to the buffalo themselves, to the swirled and stretched mozzarella is grown, housed, and made in a “Denominazione di Origine Protetta”, or Protected Designation of Origin, in Campania, Italy.

Producer/Editor: @carla_francescutti 
Director: @annamuckerman 
Field Producers/Camera: @annamuckerman, Mohamad Ahmed

node.title: How an Italian Dairy Farm Makes 11,000 Pounds of Mozzarella a Day

node.text:
Bangkok-based chefs Chudaree Tam Debhakam (@tamchudaree) and Prin Polsuk (@prinpolsuk) fish for giant river prawns in Thailand’s Sam Khok district to make kanom jeen nam ya — a noodle and curry dish chef Polsuk uncovered from an ancient text. They fashion a makeshift grill rack out of bamboo, and cook the prawns over an open flame right outside in the forest.  

Created & Directed by Paul Travis (@lannafilms) // Producers: Fern Sripungwiwat (@feasttheculture), @Carla_Francescutti, @mcgraw_wolfman //  
Production Consultant: Poonperm Paitayawat // Camera: Tin Guyson (@@tin_guyson), Kingkan Siripiriyakul (@mighty.meng) // Second Camera/Local Editor: Michael Towers  (@bangkokphotographer) // Translation & Content: Miki Thabbanthon (@miki_jung11) // Editors: @carla_francescutti, @mike.imhoff

“The fear of failure is not present in our universe,” says chef and co-owner Chintan Pandya (@chefchintan) of Dhamaka (@dhamakanyc), one of NYC’s most exciting new restaurants. He’s referring to the relentless testing and experimenting with different — ultimately delicious — variations on Indian dishes, like 16-layer goat neck dum biryani, dohl kleh (pig face salad) and goat testicle, and kidney gurda kapoora.

Director/Producer: @DanielGeneen // Camera: @Carla_Francescutti, @connorreidgram //
Editor: @Mur_F

node.title: Why Dhamaka is One of NYC's Most Exciting New Restaurants

NYC pop-up Dame (@dame_nyc) was supposed to sell fish and chips for a few weeks in the summer of 2020 during the pandemic. A year later, owners and Eater New Guard 2021 members Ed Szymanski (@ed.z.szymanski) and Patricia Howard (@patricia__howard) are still dunking hunks of hake into the deep fryer. We followed the duo as they tested out recipes six weeks before opening the doors to their permanent space in NYC’s West Village after an explosive response to their crispy battered fish.

Director/Producer: @pelin_liu // Camera: @carla_francescutti, @connorreidgram // Editor: Lucy Morales (@del_fuego)

node.title: How Chef Ed Szymanski Perfected Fish & Chips at NYC’s Dame

“The biggest misconception about soul food is that it is unhealthy, not good for you, and that it’s garbage, that it’s trash. It’s just not true,” says chef Deborah VanTrece (@chefdeborahvantrece), as she washes an enormous pile of collard greens. These leafy greens are destined for a tortellini dish with a soul food-spin — combining the traditions and ingredients used by Black chefs in the South, with global cuisines — something that VanTrece is known for at her restaurant Twisted Soul Cookhouse & Pours (@twistedsoulcookhouse) in Atlanta, Georgia. 

Producers: @pelin_liu, @meghanmccarron // Director: @pelin_liu // Camera:  @tjahedo, @laura_ayme_palacio // Editor: Scott Kan

node.title: Chef Deborah VanTrece Honors Soul Food’s History at Her Atlanta Restaurant

At dairy farm La Ferme du Champ Secret (@Fermeduchampsecret) in Normandy, France, owner Patrick Mercier is delighted by the fact that his soft, spreadable Camembert cheese has been said to have “the flavor of the barn.” That’s because this farm is one of only two remaining producers of organic, grass-fed Camembert cheese using traditional methods which “convey the ambiance of the herd” in the cheese.

Producer: @pelin_liu Field // Producer/Director: @annamuckerman // Camera: @annamuckerman, Mohamed Ahmed

Those dumplings in your freezer? They can be so much more than just dumplings. In this series, @jamesyworld shares some of his favorite easy recipes that all begin with frozen dumplings.⁣
⁣
First up: Dumpling egg pancake.⁣
⁣
Pour in a few beaten eggs when pan frying dumplings to create a fluffy golden halo around them. Garnish with fresh scallions, a little furikake, and you've yourself an impressive — and impressively simple — snack.⁣

"This is a skin contact. It's a grenache grape from Phil Coturri, a Sonoma County winery," says Nathan Cozzolino, co-owner of Rose Delights (@rose_losangeles). But he's not talking about fine wine — he's talking about ingredients for his edibles. 

The company aims to take THC and CBD infused treats to the next level — in the form of Turkish delights. Sourcing high quality ingredients and collaborating with chefs like Dominique Crenn and Manu Buffara, he makes brightly colored buzzy treats with flavors like apple and passionfruit or blueberry caipirinha.

On this week's episode of Gastropod (@gastropodcast), host Nicola Twilley (@nicolatwilley) tries one of these "delights," and learns more about the process that goes into making them. 

Head to the link in bio to listen to the full episode. 🎧

📸: @rose_losangeles

node.text:
After years of Texas-style barbecue’s dominance, mostly cooked by people with little ancestral connection to the food, Black-owned restaurants and pop-ups across Los Angeles have begun to redirect the city's smoked meat conversation back toward its roots.

Taken together, these spots are restoring the history of LA smoke one rib plate at a time. They’re also cementing the city’s barbecue legacy as an inclusive place where Texas bark, Southern sauces, and LA-specific flavor innovations can all coexist. 

In our profile link, read @overoverunder on the current Black barbecue renaissance unfolding in Los Angeles. 

📸 Eater LA photographer @wonhophoto

The world’s greatest, sweetest, most perfect mangoes are grown in Pakistan. Though the U.S. imports plenty of fruit — and despite the Pakistani mango being approved for import since 2010 — these mangoes are nearly impossible to get here. 

But all is not lost for a taste of the prized fruit — if you’ve got a contact with a WhatsApp mango importer and are willing to pay handsomely for the prized fruit and buy in bulk, that is. 

In our profile link, read @radbrowndads's deep dive into the secretive, semi-illict, high stakes world of WhatsApp mango importing.

node.text:
As restaurants across the country opt into proof of vaccination policies for prospective diners, they face coordinated online attacks from anti-vaccine trolls. In one Raleigh restaurant, that policy only applied to indoor dining and left the option of patio dining open to customers — though a cascade of calls, comments, emails, and reviews still followed the announcement. 

According to restaurant owner Richard Gusler, the main sources of the vitriol "seem to be mostly people from out of state, not people locally." He says the furor has since calmed down following the policy change, and "everyone thought we would just get killed, business-wise, and instead our business is up about 9 percent."

While the unmitigated bile of coordinated anti-vax troll attacks stays mostly online — including from commenters who will surely be raging beneath this post too — sometimes it spills over into real life. One Seattle bartender says he's received nine death threats since his bar implemented a proof-of-vaccination policy. 

Link in bio for the full story.

For the smoked pork rib tips at My Father’s Barbeque (@myfathersbbq), pitmaster Shalamar Lane (@chefshalamarlane) uses a traditional paprika and cumin spice rub, used by her Alabama-native father, that includes cracked black pepper and coarse salt often found in her mother’s Texas-style barbecue dishes. With a marriage of styles and techniques from both regions, but being served in California, chef Lane carries on her family traditions while also forging something entirely new.

Producer/Director: @Connorreidgram // Camera: @Connorreidgram, @Mur_F // Editor: @mike.imhoff

Southern California has steadily emerged as one of America’s best barbecue regions, and Los Angeles is its capital. This is Barbecue Week on @eater_la, and it's all about the city's finest smoked meats. 

In a place as diverse as Los Angeles, that means zigzagging from Texas-style stars to smoky brisket with a side of cornbread bibingka at a Filipino barbecue mainstay, to pit-roasted goat barbacoa, to char siu ribs served out of a garage. 

Tap our profile link or head to @eater_la for all the Barbecue Week stories.

Torre Lupara’s buffalo mozzarella is about an Italian as a product as you can get. The cheese is classified as DOP Mozzarella di Bufala, meaning everything from the feed the buffalo eat, to the buffalo themselves, to the swirled and stretched mozzarella is grown, housed, and made in a “Denominazione di Origine Protetta”, or Protected Designation of Origin, in Campania, Italy.
